## üé® Design Aesthetic Summary

### Contemporary Minimal Pop Art Principles

**Visual Identity:**
- **High Contrast:** Pure black and white with strategic grey usage
- **Bold Typography:** Massive ANTON and Bebas Neue headlines
- **Geometric Shapes:** Circles, squares, triangles, abstract compositions
- **Halftone Textures:** Dot patterns for depth without color
- **Screen Print Aesthetic:** Sharp edges, flat colors, bold lines
- **Brutalist Influence:** Raw, honest, functional design
- **Pop Art References:** Warhol repetition, Lichtenstein graphics
- **Bauhaus Inspiration:** Form follows function, geometric precision

**What to DO:**
‚úÖ Use pure black (#000000) and pure white (#FFFFFF) as primary colors  
‚úÖ Convert ALL images to high-contrast duotone or B&W  
‚úÖ Use massive typography for impact (ANTON at 120px+)  
‚úÖ Create geometric compositions with shapes  
‚úÖ Implement halftone and dot patterns for texture  
‚úÖ Use thick borders (2-3px) instead of soft shadows  
‚úÖ Hard cuts and wipes for transitions, not fades  
‚úÖ Invert colors on hover (black ‚Üî white)  
‚úÖ Bold, uppercase typography for headers  
‚úÖ Strategic use of negative space  
‚úÖ Asymmetric, dynamic layouts  
‚úÖ Comic book-style impact graphics  

**What NOT to DO:**
‚ùå NO COLOR - absolutely no hues beyond black/white/grey  
‚ùå No soft shadows or blurs (use hard geometric shadows)  
‚ùå No gradients (except halftone patterns)  
‚ùå No subtle fades (use hard cuts)  
‚ùå No organic shapes (keep geometric)  
‚ùå No small, timid typography  
‚ùå No excessive decoration  
‚ùå No color images (convert everything to B&W)  

### Reference Inspirations
- **Andy Warhol:** Repetition, screen printing, bold contrast
- **Roy Lichtenstein:** Ben-Day dots, comic book aesthetic, bold outlines
- **Bauhaus Movement:** Geometric forms, functional design, grid systems
- **Swiss Design:** Clean typography, grid-based layouts, minimal color
- **Brutalist Architecture:** Raw, honest materials, bold forms
- **Vintage Posters:** High contrast, bold typography, geometric shapes
- **Japanese Graphic Design:** Negative space, asymmetry, bold compositions

